China is ready to work with Timor-Leste to make a cooperation plan under the Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) and specify key areas of cooperation, Chinese State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi said on Friday. Wang made the remarks during a meeting with Timor-Leste's Prime Minister Taur Matan Ruak in Dili, the capital of Timor-Leste. Proposed by China in 2013, the BRI comprises of the Silk Road Economic Belt and the 21st Century Maritime Silk Road, and aims to build trade and infrastructure networks connecting Asia with Europe and Africa along and beyond the ancient Silk Road routes. China and Timor-Leste signed a Memorandum of Understanding for cooperation on the BRI in March 2017. Wang held talks with Timor-Leste's Foreign Minister Adaljiza Albertina Xavier Reis Magno on the same day. The two countries agreed to deepen the alignment of development strategies and deepen mutually beneficial cooperation in fields such as infrastructure, energy capacity, poverty alleviation, education and health. This year marks the 20th anniversary of the restoration of independence of Timor-Leste and the 20th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties between China and Timor-Leste. Timor-Leste is the last stop of Wang's 10-day tour in the Pacific region, following visits to Solomon Islands, Kiribati, Samoa, Fiji, Tonga, Vanuatu and Papua New Guinea. Read more: Chinese, Timor-Leste's presidents exchange congratulations on 20th anniversary of diplomatic tiesTimor-Leste's president: China contributes to global and regional economies